MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: SITE IS LOCATED ON ANTIETAM CREEK AT THE HISTORIC BURNSIDE BRIDGE JUST BELOW AN AREA WITH HIGH RECREATIONAL USE.  THE MAJOR PORTION OF THE ANTIETAM FLOWS THROUGH SOILS THAT ARE DEEP WELL DRAINED AND ARE MODER- ATELY OR MODERATELY RAPIDLY PERMEABLE WITH SLOPES FROM 0 TO 10 OR 15 PERCENT.  A SMALL PORTION OF THE SOILS ARE ALL ROCKY OR VERY ROCKY OR EXTREMELY ROCKY WITH SLOPES OF 8 TO 15 PERCENT ACCORDING TO THE NATURAL SOILS GROUPS MAPS FOR WASHINGTON COUNTY MD. MORE SPECIFICALLY THE MAJOR SOIL THROUGH WHICH THE CREEK CARVES ITS WAY IS HUNTINGTON SILT LOAM. STATION IS THE RESPONSIBILITY OF ANTIETAM NATIONAL BATTLEFIELD. OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: SITE IS LOCATED ON ANTIETAM CREEK WHERE THE CREEK ENTERS PARK PROPERTY. ANTIETAM CREEK IS THE MAJOR WATER BODY WITHIN THE PARK.  THIS CREEK FLOWS IN A NORTH/SOUTH DIRECTION THROUGH WASHINGTON COUNTY MARYLAND AND IS ONE OF THE MAJOR TRIBUTARIES TO THE POTOMAC RIVER. APPROXIMATELY TWO MILES OF THE ANTIETAM FLOW THROUGH OR ADJACENT TO THE BATTLEFIELD WITH AN AVERAGE GRADIENT OF 7.9 FEET PER MILE.  THE GROUNDWATER IS AN ALKA- LINE CALCIUM BICARBONATE IN NATURE.  THE CREEK FLOWS THROUGH A HAGERS- TOWN - DUFFIELD - FUNKSTOWN SOILS ASSOCIATION - SOILS OF LIMESTONE VAL- LEYS - AS IT APPEARS ON THE GENERAL SOIL MAP FOR WASHINGTON COUNTY MD. MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: SITE IS LOCATED ON ANTIETAM CREEK WHERE THE CREEK LEAVES PARK PROPERTY. THE HUNTINGTON SILT LOAM FALLS INTO CAPABILITY UNIT I-6 WHICH CONSISTS OF NEARLY LEVEL WELL-DRAINED FRIABLE SOILS ON FLOOD PLAINS AND ON LOW STREAM TERRACES.  THE WOODLAND SUITABILITY GROUP FOR THIS SOIL IS FL AN EXCELLENT SOIL FOR WOODLAND. MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: SITE IS LOCATED AT MUMMA SPRING SOURCE. THIS STREAM IS FED BY THE NATURAL SPRING ON THE HISTORIC MUMMA FARM FLOWING INTO A HOLDING POND OFF OF PARK PROPERTY. THE STREAM FLOWS THRU AN AREA THAT WAS PASTURED IT HAS NOW BEEN ALLOWED TO GROW UP AND RETURN TO AN OLD FIELD SITUATION THIS STREAM FLOWS THROUGH THE HAGERSTOWN-DUFFIELD-FRANKSTOWN GENERAL SOIL ASSOCIATION SOILS OF LIMESTONE VALLEYS. THE NATURAL SOILS GROUPS ARE INITIALLY THE DEEP WELL DRAINED SOILS THAT ARE MODERATELY OR MODERATELY RAPIDLY PERMEABLE WITH SLOPES OF 0 TO 10 PERCENT. MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: SITE IS LOCATED AT THE POINT WHERE THE SPRING LEAVES ANTIETAM PARK. THE MORE SPECIFIC SOILS TYPES ARE THE HAGERSTOWN SILT LOAM 0 TO 8 PERCENT SLOPES MODERATELY ERODED. THIS UNIT FALLS INTO CAPABILITY IIE-1 DEEP WELL DRAINED GENTLY SLOPING SOILS THAT HAVE A FRIABLE SURFACE LAYER DEVELOPED IN OR STRONGLY INFLUENCED BY MATERIAL THAT WEATHERED FROM LIMESTONE. A SECOND MAJOR SOIL TYPE IS THE HAGERSTOWN VERY ROCKY SILTY CLAY LOAM 3 TO 15 PERCENT SLOPES MODERATELY ERODED. THIS TYPE IS ASSIGNED CAPABILITY UNIT VIS-1 SLOPING TO STEEP WELL DRAINED VERY ROCKY SOILS THAT ARE LIMITED BY ROCKINESS AND HAZARD OF EROSION. ROCKS ARE OUTCROPS OF LIMESTONE. MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Station FRSP_NPS_05 is in North Wilderness Run at a no longer existent cattle crossing in the Wilderness unit of the Fredericksburg and Spotsylvania County Battlefields Memorial National Military Park (FRSP) just upstream of FRSP_NPS_WI01.  This is one of the original water quality monitoring stations in a program, begun in 1993, to monitor water quality at streams in/near the park thought to be most likely impacted by urban and agricultural pollution.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Station FRSP_NPS_08 is in the Rappahannock River at a tidal flat below Chatham Heights adjoining the Fredericksburg Battlefield unit  of the Fredericksburg and Spotsylvania County Battlefields Memorial National Military Park (FRSP).  This is one of the original water quality monitoring stations in a program, begun in 1993, to monitor water quality at streams in/near the park thought to be most likely impacted by urban and agricultural pollution.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: This is a small creek located in northern Chancellorsville Battlefield Park.  The creek consists mostly of runs with a few small riffles.  To reach this creek, you can use the section of the History Loop Trail north of Bullock Road.  The trail intersects the creek by means of a small wooden bridge.  The water near the bridge is full of sediment and there does not appear to be a well-mixed area for sampling.  The area surrounding the creek is densely vegetated so samples may have to be taken downstream from one of the riffles near the bridge.  This creek originates in a wooded section of the park and flows northwest to where it exits the park at the northern boundary.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: This is a very small first order creek that feeds into the creek system near Berry-Paxton Drive in southern Chancellorsville Battlefield Park.  The creek consists almost entirely of shallow runs bordered by vegetation.  The creek is accessible from the Fairview walking trail.  The creek originates within the park boundaries in a forested area and flows southeast through Fairview field before joining the into the creek system south of Berry-Paxton Drive.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: This creek is another first order creek in the creek system south of Berry-Paxton Drive.  The creek also consists almost entirely of shallow runs and pools.  The creek originates in a forested region inside the park boundaries and flows southwest through a wooded area to its junction with the creek system.  The creek is most easily accessible from Berry-Paxton Drive.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: This creek is a first order creek that becomes Nine Mile Run. The sampling site is located on a creek that originates inside park boundaries just downstream of some single-family houses.  It flows northwest through Ashleigh field towards a wooded area where it joins with a tributary from Big Meadow Swamp before exiting the park.  The sampling area contains a mixture of shallow pools, runs, and riffles.  This creek is accessible from either McLaws Drive or Plank Road.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: The sampling site is located on Lewis Run where it enters southern Chancellorsville Battlefield Park. The creek originates outside of the park boundaries and winds through housing areas and two impoundments.  Once inside the park, the creek flows southeast and joins the waterway leading to the Ni River.  This creek contains a mixture of pools, runs and riffles of varying depth.  This creek is accessible from the bridge where it crosses under Sickles Drive.  The water pools under the bridge so the sampling site is actually located upstream of the bridge in a riffle area.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: This sampling site is located after the junction of the creeks from Fairview field and Fairview Cemetery and just before the creek systems exit from Chancellorsville Battlefield Park.  The creek is mainly composed of runs and pools.  The area upstream of the site is entirely within park boundaries.  The creek runs southwest and exits the park right before its entry into the second impoundment area of Lewis Run.  The site is accessible from the area where the waterway passes under Stuart Drive just south of Berry-Paxton Drive.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: This creek consists almost entirely of pools and runs.  The sampling site is located off the bridge on Furnace Road in southern Chancellorsville Battlefield Park and is downstream of the second junction of creeks that originate outside of the park boundaries.  This site is also downstream of the sampling site on Lewis Run (CR05).  The creek runs southeast through a forested area of the park before exiting the property.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: The sampling site is located on the northern branch of Deep Run that crosses Lee Drive in Fredericksburg Battlefield Park.  The creek origin is outside the park boundaries in a residential area.  The creek flows southeast across the park to its exit east of Lee Drive.  There is a bridge from the walking trail and several houses upstream of the sampling site.  The creek is a mixture of riffles, runs and pools.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: The southern branch of Deep Run is located in Fredericksburg Battlefield Park about  mile south of the first crossing of the creek on Lee Drive.  The watershed upstream of the sampling site contains residential houses and hiking trails.  The origin of the creek is outside of park boundaries and the creek flows northeast through the park to its exit located directly east of Lee Drive.  The creek is comprised of a mixture of riffles, runs and pools.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: This sampling site is located on the stream that flows past the CRO building in Fredericksburg Battlefield Park.  The watershed upstream of the creek is primarily located in a residential area.  The stream originates outside of park boundaries and crosses through the park on its way to the Rappahannock River.  This is a very shallow stream containing riffles, runs and pools.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: The sampling site on Hazel Run is located near the National Cemetery in Fredericksburg Battlefield Park.  The creek originates outside park boundaries in a commercial, industrial, and residential area.  The waterway winds through the park on its way to the Rappahannock River and is most easily accessible from Plank Road.  The creek contains a mixture of riffles, runs, and pools.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: The creek at Burnside Drive in Spotsylvania Battlefield Park is accessible by the bridge where the creek runs under the road.  This creek originates in the park boundaries in a forested area between Gordon Drive and Burnside Drive and flows east through the park to its exit north of Burnside Drive.  The creek contains a mixture of riffles, runs and pools and has lots of beaver activity in this creek.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: The creek in a Bloody Angle Field in Spotsylvania Battlefield Park originates in park boundaries and flows northeast to join the Ni River.  This very shallow creek is accessible from the access road that goes to the ruins.  It is composed primarily of runs.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: The sampling area on Wilderness Run is located near the picnic area off Hill-Ewell Drive in Wilderness Battlefield Park.  The creek originates outside of the park boundaries in a forested area and once inside the park, winds northeast past agricultural lands before it joins with South Wilderness Run and exits the park at Plank Road.  This sampling area contains a mixture of pools, runs and riffles.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: This section of Wilderness Run will be accessed by the bridge off Hill-Ewell Drive in Wilderness Battlefield Park.  The creek originates outside of the park in a cleared section of woodlands and flows northeast through the park.  The watershed upstream of the sampling site contains primarily woodlands and agricultural areas.  Downstream from the site, the creek flows into Wilderness Run lake and then joins North Wilderness Run before exiting the park at Plank Road.  This creek contains mostly pools and runs.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: The sampling site at Elwood is located downstream of the junction of North Wilderness Run and South Wilderness Run.  The site is accessible from the field beside the main road into Elwood.  The watershed upstream of the site is a combination of residential, agricultural and woodland areas.  After Elwood, Wilderness Run flows northeast out of the park at Plank Road.  This section of Wilderness Run contains mainly pools and runs.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: There is a section of Brock Run that flows through the area of Wilderness Battlefield Park known as Hamiltons Thicket.  The creek should flow southeast through the wooded region.  This area is a new acquisition to the park.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: This creek flows through the area of Wilderness Battlefield that is north of Constitution Highway.  This site was a part of the original water monitoring plan of the park back in the 1990s.  The creek can also be accessed from its intersection with Constitution Hwy near Plank Road.  The watershed upstream of the sampling site contains residential and commercial areas.  The creek contains primarily runs and pools.
